  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This article, titled \"Do organisms need an impact factor? Citations of key biological resources including model organisms reveal usage patterns and impact,\" provides a vital exploration of model organisms and their usage within the biological research community. Authored by a diverse team across several prominent institutions, the preprint has already been cited three times, indicating an influential discourse in the biological sciences.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The investigation presented in this preprint, available through bioRxiv, addresses the importance of impact factors on the usage and citation patterns of biological resources, particularly model organisms. The authors, including notable researchers from institutions such as Cincinnati Children's Hospital Medical Center and the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School, highlight how understanding these patterns can impact scientific research and its dissemination.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work's immediate influence is evident, as it has garnered three citations, predominantly from the United States and France, showcasing its reach across significant geographic boundaries. Moreover, the citing venues include additional preprints and articles, reflecting the work's impact on the ongoing academic conversation within the realm of biological data utilization.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Crucially, the authors emphasize transparency and reproducibility, evidenced by the inclusion of Research Resource Identifiers (RRIDs)\u2014three in total. This commitment aids researchers in locating and utilizing the resources discussed, thereby enriching their research endeavors and fostering a culture of reproducible science.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, this preprint has successfully transitioned to formal publication, underscoring the rigorous academic validation it has undergone. This dual presence\u2014as both a preprint and a peer-reviewed article\u2014enhances its visibility and allows for broader engagement with the research community, demonstrating effective early sharing practices that can inspire further inquiry in the field.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, this work presents a significant contribution to the understanding of biological resource utilization, making strides in how researchers engage with model organisms. The data and insights offered can spur future research and highlight the ongoing evolution of biological sciences, ultimately adding to the foundational knowledge within the discipline.</p>",
